window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>1","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"Which of the following organisms does not exist as a single cell?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amoeba","B":"Euglena","C":"Volvox","D":"Chlamydomonas"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Volvox does not exist as a single cell. Volvox is a spherical multicellular green alga, which contains many small biflagellate somatic cells and a few large, non-motile reproductive cells called gonidia, and swims with a characteristic rolling motion with a distinct anterior and posterior.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>2","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"Which of the following features of Paramecium is not an advancement over Amoeba? The possession of","images":[],"options":{"A":"definite shape","B":"cilia","C":"oral groove","D":"nucleus"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Both Paramecium and Amoeba possess a nucleus, which is an essential organelle that controls all the cell activities and contains genetic material. However, the nucleus in Paramecium is fixed in one position, while that of Amoeba is not fixed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>3","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following diseases results from the deficiency of insulin?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Cretinism","B":"Goitre","C":"Beri-beri","D":"Diabetes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Diabetes mellitus is a chronic heterogeneous metabolic disorder with complex pathogenesis. It is characterized by elevated blood glucose levels or hyperglycemia, which results from abnormalities in either insulin secretion or insulin action or both.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>4","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Root hairs absorb water from the soil by","images":[],"options":{"A":"diffusion","B":"osmosis","C":"plasmolysis","D":"translocation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Root hairs absorb water from the soil by the process of osmosis. The root hairs take water from the soil by a process called osmosis. In osmosis, water molecules move from a region of higher concentration to a region of lower concentration through a semi-permeable membrane. The concentration of the water molecules is lower in the root hair than in the soil. So the water moves into the root hairs through osmosis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>5","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"One of the similarities between algae and mosses is their possession of","images":[],"options":{"A":"chlorophyll","B":"stem","C":"leaves","D":"roots"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Algae and mosses are both photosynthetic organisms, meaning they have the ability to convert light energy, usually from the sun, into chemical energy in the form of glucose or other sugars. This process of photosynthesis is facilitated by the pigment chlorophyll, which is present in both algae and mosses. Chlorophyll absorbs light energy, particularly energy in the blue and red wavelengths, and uses this energy to combine carbon dioxide and water to produce glucose. This is why both algae and mosses possess chlorophyll. The other options - stem, leaves, and roots - are not correct because while mosses may have structures that resemble these, algae do not have differentiated structures like stems, leaves, or roots.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>6","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"The vessel that carries blood from the heart to the lungs is called an artery because it","images":[],"options":{"A":"contains oxygenated blood","B":"contains more blood than the other vessels","C":"carries blood away from the heart","D":"has thick inelastic wall"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The vessel that carries blood from the heart to the lungs is called an artery because it carries blood away from the heart. The term 'artery' is used to describe any blood vessel that carries blood away from the heart, regardless of the blood's oxygenation status. The pulmonary artery, in this case, carries deoxygenated blood from the heart to the lungs for oxygenation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>7","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"During anaerobic respiration in skeletal muscles, pyruvic acid is","images":[],"options":{"A":"reduced to lactic acid","B":"oxidized to ethanol","C":"oxidized to lactic acid","D":"reduced to water"},"answer":"A","explanation":"During anaerobic respiration in skeletal muscles, pyruvic acid is reduced to lactic acid. When people exercise, sometimes the oxygen supply needed to power muscles is depleted more quickly than it can be restored. When this happens, muscle cells temporarily switch to anaerobic respiration to generate energy. Lactic acid builds in the muscles as a result of this process. Oversaturation of lactic acid leads to muscle cramps and fatigue.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>8","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Use the information on the stages involved in conjugation to answer the  question below  I. Transfer of one cell content into the adjacent cell   ll. Formation of a conjugation tube   III. Secretion of thick wall to form a zygospore   IV. Formation of a protuberance   V. Germination of a filament    Which of the following organisms exhibits 'the stages listed above during conjugation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Chlamydomonas","B":"Euglena","C":"Spirogyra","D":"Volvox"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The conjugation processes of a filamentous freshwater green alga Spirogyra varians were examined using FITC-lectins. Conjugation comprised five steps: 1) aligning with adjacent filaments, 2) formation of conjugation protru-sion (papilla), 3) fusion of the protrusions, 4) formation of conjugation tube,and 5) formation of zygotes","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>9","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"Use the information on the stages involved in conjugation to answer the  question below  I. Transfer of one cell content into the adjacent cell   ll. Formation of a conjugation tube   III. Secretion of thick wall to form a zygospore   IV. Formation of a protuberance   V. Germination of a filament   Which of the following arrangements is the correct sequence of the process?","images":[],"options":{"A":"II, I, IV, V and III","B":"IV, II, I, III and V","C":"IV, I, II, V and III","D":"V, II, III, IV and I"},"answer":"A","explanation":"This means that the formation of a conjugation tube comes first, followed by the transfer of one cell content into the adjacent cell, then the formation of a protuberance, germination of a filament and finally secretion of a thick wall to form a zygospore.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>10","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ALIMENTARY SYSTEM","question":"The teeth used for tearing and cutting are","images":[],"options":{"A":"canine and molars","B":"premolar and incisors","C":"molar and incisors","D":"canine and incisors"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The teeth used for tearing and cutting are the canines and incisors. Canines are the sharp, pointed teeth that sit next to the incisors and are used for tearing food. Incisors are the teeth at the front of the mouth and they are used for cutting food. Therefore, the correct answer is 'canine and incisors'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>11","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Turgor pressure occurs in a cell when the?","images":[],"options":{"A":"volume of its cell sap increases","B":"cell loses water to its environment","C":"volume of cell decreases","D":"cell is put in an isotonic solution"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Turgor pressure occurs in a cell when the volume of its cell sap increases. Turgor pressure is the force within the cell that pushes the plasma membrane against the cell wall. It is primarily caused by the osmotic flow of water and occurs in cells that have a cell wall, such as plant cells and fungi. When water enters the cell, it causes the central vacuole to expand and push against the cell wall. This pressure is what gives the plant its rigidity and support.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>12","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following bones is illustrated in the diagram?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Tibia","B":"Humerus","C":"Patella","D":"Scapula"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Scapula, also called shoulder blade, either of two large bones of the shoulder girdle in vertebrates. In humans they are triangular and lie on the upper back between the levels of the second and eighth ribs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>13","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The part labelled l in the diagram is for the attachment of","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"ribs","B":"biceps","C":"shoulder muscles","D":"the vertebral column"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The part labelled l in the diagram is for the attachment of shoulder muscles. The diagram shown is a Scapula, also called shoulder blade.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>14","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following bones forms a joint at the point labelled II in the diagram?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Humerus","B":"Sternum","C":"Radius","D":"Femur"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Humerus forms a joint at the point labelled II in the diagram.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>15","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TRANSPORT SYSTEM","question":"Which of the following is correct about the transverse section of a vein, when compared with that of an artery?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The lumen of a vein is wider than that of an artery","B":"The endothelium of the vein is thinner than that of an artery","C":"There are more smooth muscles in a vein than in an artery","D":"There are valves in veins but not in arteries."},"answer":"D","explanation":"There are valves in veins but not in arteries is correct.Unlike arteries, veins contain valves that ensure blood flows in only one direction. (Arteries don't require valves because pressure from the heart is so strong that blood is only able to flow in one direction.) Valves also help blood travel back to the heart against the force of gravity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>16","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Terrestrial plants exchange gases through the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"chloroplast","B":"stomata","C":"lenticels","D":"root-cells"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Chloroplasts are organelles found in plant cells where photosynthesis takes place, but they are not directly involved in gas exchange.  Stomata: These are small openings on the surface of leaves that allow for gas exchange between the plant and the atmosphere.  Lenticels: These are small openings on the surface of stems and roots that allow for gas exchange.  Root cells: While root cells themselves don't exchange gases directly, roots have tiny hair-like structures called root hairs that increase the surface area for gas exchange.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>17","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Glomerular filtrate contains","images":[],"options":{"A":"no glucose","B":"amino acids","C":"no proteins","D":"urea"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Glomerular filtrate is the liquid that has been filtered out of the blood by the glomerulus into the Bowman's capsule in the kidneys. It contains everything that blood plasma does (such as water, glucose, amino acids, urea) except for proteins. Proteins are too large to pass through the glomerular filter. Therefore, the glomerular filtrate contains no proteins.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>18","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following is not a function of the liver in mammals?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Storage of some vitamins","B":"Conversion of glycogen into glucose","C":"Deamination of excess nitrogenous substances","D":"Filtration of urea from the blood."},"answer":"D","explanation":"The liver in mammals performs a variety of functions including the storage of some vitamins, conversion of glycogen into glucose, and deamination of excess nitrogenous substances. However, the filtration of urea from the blood is not a function of the liver but rather the kidneys. The kidneys filter blood, removing waste products like urea, and also maintain the balance of electrolytes in the blood.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>19","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Iodine is needed by a patient suffering from a malfunctioning of the","images":[],"options":{"A":"salivary gland","B":"thyroid gland","C":"adrenal gland","D":"sebaceous gland"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Iodine is needed by a patient suffering from a malfunctioning of the thyroid gland. The thyroid gland uses iodine to produce thyroid hormones that help control growth, repair damaged cells and support a healthy metabolism. Therefore, a deficiency in iodine can lead to problems with the thyroid gland, such as goiter or hypothyroidism.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>20","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The medulla oblongata controls all the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"heart beat","B":"breathing rate","C":"blood pressure","D":"balance and posture"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The medulla oblongata is a part of the brain that controls autonomic functions such as heart rate, breathing, and blood pressure. However, balance and posture are primarily controlled by the cerebellum, not the medulla oblongata. Therefore, the correct answer is 'balance and posture'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>21","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Which of the following statements about short sight is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The eyeball is too short","B":"The cornea of the eyeball is too curved","C":"The images fall in front of the retina","D":"It can be corrected by using concave lenses"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Short sight, also known as myopia, is a common vision condition in which you can see objects near to you clearly, but objects farther away are blurry. It occurs when the shape of your eye causes light rays to bend (refract) incorrectly, focusing the images in front of the retina instead of directly on the retina. This can be caused by the eyeball being too long, not too short, or the cornea being too curved. Therefore, the statement 'The eyeball is too short' is not correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>22","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Hypermetropia is corrected by the use of","images":[],"options":{"A":"concave lenses","B":"convex lenses","C":"cylindrical lenses","D":"contact lenses"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Hypermetropia, also known as farsightedness, is a condition of the eye where the light that comes in does not directly focus on the retina but behind it. This condition can be corrected by the use of convex lenses. Convex lenses are thicker at the center than at the edges, they converge light rays to a point. When a convex lens is used, it bends the light rays inward to directly focus on the retina, thus correcting the vision.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>23","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"The structure labelled I is the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"oviduct","B":"ovary","C":"uterus","D":"funnel"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The structure labelled I is the oviduct. The oviduct in mammals, is the passageway from an ovary. In human females this is more usually known as the Fallopian tube or uterine tube.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>24","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"In which of the labelled structures does implantation take place?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"IV","D":"VI"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The structure labelled IV is where implantation takes place.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>25","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"Which of the following indicates the direction of the movement of a sperm introduced into the female reproductive system?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"III \u2192 II \u2192 I \u2192 IV","B":"VI \u2192 V \u2192 IV \u2192 I","C":"V \u2192 IV \u2192 I \u2192 III","D":"VI \u2192 IV \u2192 I \u2192 III"},"answer":"B","explanation":"VI \u2192 V \u2192 IV \u2192 I indicates the direction of the movement of a sperm introduced into the female reproductive system","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>26","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTIVE SYSTEM OF MAMMALS","question":"Which of the labelled parts is responsible for the release of ripe ovum?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"VI","B":"III","C":"II","D":"I"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The labelled part III is responsible for the release of ripe ovum","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>27","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"During germination of seeds water is taken by the process of","images":[],"options":{"A":"diffusion","B":"hydrolysis","C":"imbibition","D":"translocation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During the germination of seeds, water is taken up by the process of imbibition. Imbibition is the process where water is absorbed by solids-colloids causing them to enormously increase in volume. The absorption of water by seeds leads to the swelling of seeds which breaks the seed coat and leads to germination. The other options are not correct. Diffusion is the movement of molecules from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. Hydrolysis is a chemical process in which a molecule is cleaved into two parts by the addition of a molecule of water. Translocation is the movement of materials from leaves to other tissues throughout the plant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>28","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following is not a characteristics feature of a wind dispersed fruit?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Lightweight","B":"winged apparatus","C":"Flossy structure","D":"Buoyancy"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Wind dispersed fruits have certain characteristics that aid their dispersal by wind. These include being lightweight, having a winged apparatus or a flossy structure to catch the wind. Buoyancy, however, is a characteristic of water-dispersed fruits/seeds, not wind-dispersed fruits. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Buoyancy'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>29","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"During photosynthesis, light energy is always absorbed by the","images":[],"options":{"A":"shoot","B":"water","C":"chlorophyll","D":"enzyme"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During photosynthesis, light energy is always absorbed by the chlorophyll. Chlorophyll (also chlorophyl) is any of several related green pigments found in cyanobacteria and in the chloroplasts of algae and plants.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>30","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Use the information below on factors required during photosynthesis to answer the two questions  I. CO2   II. Chlorophyll   III. Water   IV. ATP   V NADPH2.    Which of the above factors can be a limiting factor for the process to proceed?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I and II only","B":"I and III only","C":"I and IV only","D":"I, III and IV only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In photosynthesis, the process can be limited by several factors including light intensity, carbon dioxide concentration and temperature. In the given options, CO2 (I) and Water (III) can be limiting factors. Chlorophyll (II) is necessary for photosynthesis but it's not typically considered a limiting factor because it's usually present in sufficient quantities in plants. ATP (IV) and NADPH (V) are products of the light-dependent reactions and are used in the light-independent reactions of photosynthesis, but they are not typically considered limiting factors because they are produced in the process itself. Therefore, the correct answer is 'I and III only'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>31","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : PLANT NUTRITION","question":"Use the information below on factors required during photosynthesis to answer the two questions  I. CO2   II. Chlorophyll   III. Water   IV. ATP   V NADPH2.   The factors required for the dark phase of photosynthesis are","images":[],"options":{"A":"III and IV only","B":"III and V only","C":"III, IV and V only","D":"IV and V only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The dark phase of photosynthesis, also known as the Calvin cycle, requires:  - ATP (IV) to provide energy  - NADPH2 (V) to provide reducing power    These two factors are produced in the light-dependent reactions and are used to convert CO2 into glucose in the Calvin cycle.  Water (III) is a reactant in the light-dependent reactions, not the dark phase.  Chlorophyll (II) is a pigment that plays a critical role in absorbing light energy in the light-dependent reactions, but is not directly involved in the dark phase.    CO2 (I) is a reactant that is used in the Calvin cycle, but it is not a factor that is required for the dark phase to proceed.    Therefore, the correct answer is  IV and V only, as ATP and NADPH2 are the only two factors that are required for the dark phase of photosynthesis to proceed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>32","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"In water- culture experiments the culture solutions are protected from sunlight in order to","images":[],"options":{"A":"control the temperature of the culture solution","B":"prevent algae from growing in the solution","C":"prevent the minerals in the solution from being destroyed","D":"allow the minerals to be used up at room temperature"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In water-culture experiments, the culture solutions are protected from sunlight primarily to prevent algae from growing in the solution. Algae are photosynthetic organisms that require sunlight to grow. If the culture solutions are exposed to sunlight, it can lead to the growth of algae, which can contaminate the solution and interfere with the experiment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>33","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"The importance of a balanced diet is to","images":[],"options":{"A":"maintain constant size of an animal","B":"provide good taste in the food","C":"increase the effectiveness of digestion","D":"provide good health for an individual"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A balanced diet is important for providing good health for an individual. A balanced diet is one that gives your body the nutrients it needs to function correctly. It consists of the proper quantities and proportions of foods needed to maintain health or growth. It does not necessarily maintain constant size of an animal, provide good taste in the food or increase the effectiveness of digestion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>34","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : FEEDING HABITS","question":"The dentition of a herbivore is distinct from that of other animals due to the presence of","images":[],"options":{"A":"diastema","B":"cusps on molar teeth","C":"canines","D":"ridges on molar teeth"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The dentition of a herbivore is distinct from that of other animals due to the presence of diastema. A diastema is a space or gap between two teeth. Many species of mammals have diastemata as a normal feature, most commonly between the incisors and molars.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>35","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following statements is true?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Ptyalin acts on proteins to give amino acid","B":"Lactase acts on maltose to give amino acid","C":"Pepsin acts on proteins to give peptide","D":"Peptide acts on starch to give maltose"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Pepsin is an enzyme that breaks down proteins into smaller peptides (a peptide is a compound consisting of 2 or more amino acids). This process is known as proteolysis. This is why the statement 'Pepsin acts on proteins to give peptide' is true. The other options are incorrect because Ptyalin (also known as salivary amylase) acts on starch to give maltose, not on proteins to give amino acids. Lactase acts on lactose to give glucose and galactose, not on maltose to give amino acids. And peptides are the products of protein breakdown, they do not act on starch to give maltose.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>36","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Which of the following organisms can be found in fresh water habitat?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Sargassum and dog fish","B":"Red mangrove and pond skater","C":"Sargassum and red mangrove","D":"Spirogyra and pond skater"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Spirogyra and pond skater can be found in fresh water habitat. Spirogyra is a type of green algae that is commonly found in fresh water. Pond skaters, also known as water striders, are insects that are able to walk on the surface of water, and they are typically found in fresh water habitats. The other options include organisms that are not typically found in fresh water. Sargassum is a type of seaweed that is typically found in marine environments, and dog fish are a type of shark that is also found in the ocean. Red mangroves are trees that grow in salt water or brackish water environments.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>37","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following is not a biotic factor?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Parasites","B":"Predators","C":"Grazers","D":"Pressure"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Biotic factors are living or once-living organisms in the ecosystem. These are obtained from the biosphere and are capable of reproduction. Examples of biotic factors include any animals, plants, trees, grass, bacteria, moss, or molds that you might find in an ecosystem. In this context, parasites, predators, and grazers are all biotic factors as they are living organisms. Pressure, on the other hand, is an abiotic factor. Abiotic factors are non-living physical and chemical elements in the ecosystem. Abiotic resources are usually obtained from the lithosphere, atmosphere, and hydrosphere. Examples of abiotic factors are sunlight, water, air, soil, humidity, pH, temperature, wind, precipitation, altitude, light intensity, etc. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Pressure'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>38","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Desert plants are usually called","images":[],"options":{"A":"hydrophytes","B":"mesophytes","C":"xerophytes","D":"sporophytes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Desert plants are usually called xerophytes. Plants that are adapted to survive in physiologically dry conditions are called xerophytes. They have special adaptations to prevent loss of water, and also store some water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>39","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The secchi disc is used to measure","images":[],"options":{"A":"speed of flow of water","B":"specific gravity of water","C":"turbidity of water","D":"depth of water"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Secchi disc is used to measure the turbidity of water. Turbidity refers to the cloudiness or haziness of a fluid caused by large numbers of individual particles that are generally invisible to the naked eye, similar to smoke in air. The measurement is done by lowering the disc in the water. The depth at which the pattern on the disc is no longer visible is taken as a measure of the transparency of the water. Thus, it indirectly measures the amount of particles present in the water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>40","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Soil factors in an ecosystem are referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"topographic","B":"climatic","C":"biotic","D":"edaphic"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Soil factors in an ecosystem are referred to as edaphic factors. Edaphic refers to soil conditions, so it's the term used to denote the influence of soil on living organisms, including both plants and animals. These factors include soil structure, composition, moisture, pH level, and temperature. They can significantly affect the types of plant species that grow in a particular region, as well as the abundance and health of those plants. Options A, B, and C are incorrect because topographic refers to the physical features of a region, climatic refers to the weather conditions over a long period, and biotic refers to the living organisms in an ecosystem.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>41","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"A known weight of soil sample was oven-dried to obtain a constant weight. The loss in weight was due to loss of","images":[],"options":{"A":"organic matter only","B":"water only","C":"water and organic matter","D":"inorganic matter and water"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The process of oven-drying a soil sample is used to remove the moisture content in the soil. The heat from the oven causes the water in the soil to evaporate, leading to a loss in weight. Organic matter and inorganic matter are not affected by this process as they do not evaporate at the temperatures used in oven-drying. Therefore, the loss in weight of the soil sample is due to the loss of water only.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>42","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Carbon is added to the atmosphere by the following processes except","images":[],"options":{"A":"respiration","B":"burning","C":"photosynthesis","D":"volcanic eruption"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Carbon is added to the atmosphere through processes such as respiration, burning, and volcanic eruption. However, photosynthesis is a process that removes carbon dioxide from the atmosphere. In photosynthesis, plants absorb carbon dioxide and sunlight to produce glucose and oxygen. Therefore, photosynthesis does not add carbon to the atmosphere, but rather removes it.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>43","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following is a means of measuring primary production?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Rate of reproduction of animals","B":"Life span of an organism","C":"Number of predators in an environment","D":"harvested plants in a unit area"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Primary production is the synthesis of organic compounds from atmospheric or aqueous carbon dioxide. It principally occurs through the process of photosynthesis, which uses light as its source of energy. Primary production can be measured by the amount of harvested plants in a unit area. This is because the amount of harvested plants represents the amount of organic compounds (or biomass) that has been produced in that area. Therefore, the correct answer is 'harvested plants in a unit area'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>44","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"A situation whereby some mammals remain inactive throughout dry and hot seasons is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"aestivation","B":"dormancy","C":"burrowing","D":"incubation"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Aestivation, also spelled estivation, is a state of animal dormancy, similar to hibernation, characterized by inactivity and a lowered metabolic rate, that is entered in response to high temperatures and arid conditions. It takes place during times of heat and dryness, the hot dry season, which are often the summer months. In contrast to hibernation, when animals slow their metabolic rate to save energy and survive the winter with scarce food, aestivation is entered in response to drought to prevent desiccation, or drying up. Therefore, the correct answer is 'aestivation'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>45","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following factors may not affect living organisms in an aquatic habitat?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Turbidity","B":"Temperature","C":"Humidity","D":"Light"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In an aquatic habitat, factors such as turbidity, temperature, and light can significantly affect the living organisms. Turbidity refers to the cloudiness or haziness of a fluid caused by large numbers of individual particles that are generally invisible to the naked eye. This can affect the amount of light that penetrates the water, which can in turn affect photosynthesis in aquatic plants. Temperature can affect the metabolic rates of aquatic organisms. Light is necessary for photosynthesis in aquatic plants. However, humidity refers to the amount of water vapor in the air. Aquatic organisms, living in water, would not be directly affected by the humidity of the air above their habitat. Therefore, humidity may not affect living organisms in an aquatic habitat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>46","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : MICROORGANISMS IN ACTION","question":"Which of the following parasites is a flatworm?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Plasmodium","B":"Trypanosoma","C":"Ascaris","D":"Schistosoma"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Schistosoma is a genus of flatworms, also known as blood flukes, and they are parasitic. They belong to the phylum Platyhelminthes, which is characterized by flat, ribbon-like bodies. Plasmodium and Trypanosoma are protozoan parasites, not flatworms, and Ascaris is a roundworm, which belongs to the phylum Nematoda.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>47","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"During prolonged exercises, glucose in the muscle is convened to","images":[],"options":{"A":"pyruvic acid","B":"lactic acid","C":"co- enzyme","D":"ethanol"},"answer":"B","explanation":"During prolonged exercises, the body needs to produce energy for the muscles to continue functioning. This energy is produced through a process called glycolysis, where glucose is broken down in the absence of oxygen (anaerobic conditions) to produce lactic acid. This process is known as lactic acid fermentation. The lactic acid can cause muscle fatigue and pain, but it is later removed from the muscles when oxygen becomes available. Therefore, the correct answer is lactic acid.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>48","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : POLLUTION OF THE ATMOSPHERE","question":"Which of the following is an effect of carbon monoxide on man?","images":[],"options":{"A":"irritating the skin","B":"Reducing oxygen carrying capacity of blood","C":"Causing gene mutation","D":"Destroying white blood cells."},"answer":"B","explanation":"Carbon monoxide (CO) is a poisonous gas that can be harmful when inhaled in large amounts. The danger of CO is its ability to bind with the hemoglobin in red blood cells, forming carboxyhemoglobin, which prevents the hemoglobin from carrying oxygen. This reduces the oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood, leading to oxygen deprivation in tissues and organs. The other options are incorrect as CO does not irritate the skin, cause gene mutation, or destroy white blood cells.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>49","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : SOIL, WATER, WILDLIFE, FOREST AND MINERALS","question":"Which of the following is a renewable natural resources?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Air","B":"Timber","C":"Soil","D":"Mineral"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Timber is a renewable natural resource because trees can be replanted and regrown. Air, soil, and minerals are also natural resources, but they are not considered renewable in the same way because their availability is not directly dependent on human actions.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>50","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Which of the following resources is competed for by organisms in the desert?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Light","B":"Temperature","C":"Oxygen","D":"Water"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In a desert environment, water is the most scarce resource and therefore, it is the resource most competed for by organisms. Light is abundant in desert environments, temperature is not a resource, and oxygen is not typically limited in desert environments.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>51","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The major types of man's finger prints do not include","images":[],"options":{"A":"arch","B":"compound","C":"simple","D":"loop"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The major types of man's finger prints do not include simple.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>52","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following is an example of discontinuous variation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Height of students","B":"Complexion of beauty contestants","C":"Blood groups of patients","D":"Weight of weight lifters"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Discontinuous variation is a type of genetic variation where there are distinct categories or groups, and individuals fall into one of these groups with no intermediates. Blood groups of patients is an example of discontinuous variation because blood groups are distinct categories (A, B, AB, O) with no intermediates.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>53","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following statements is correct about variation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Offsprings are different from their parents only","B":"Offsprings from the same parents look alike","C":"Offsprings differ from their ancestors but look like their immediate parents","D":"offsprings differ from their ancestors and from each other"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Variation refers to the differences in physical traits among individuals from the same species. It is a fundamental aspect of life on Earth, and it is the driving force of evolution. Offsprings differ from their ancestors and from each other due to genetic variation. This variation comes from two main sources: mutation and recombination of genes during sexual reproduction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>54","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : LINKAGE, SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"Which of the following statements about sex determination is correct? At fertility","images":[],"options":{"A":"the probability of male to female offspring is 1/2","B":"the Y chromosome of the father decreases the probability of having a male child to 3/4","C":"the xx chromosome of the mother decreases the probability of having a female child to 3/4","D":"the vigour of either parents determines the sex of the offspring"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Sex determination in humans is determined by the 23rd pair of chromosomes, also known as the sex chromosomes. Females have two of the same kind of sex chromosome (XX), while males have two distinct sex chromosomes (XY). The sperm cells from the male can carry either an X or a Y chromosome, while the egg cells from the female only carry an X chromosome. Therefore, the probability of having a male or female offspring is 1/2, depending on whether the sperm cell carrying the X or Y chromosome fertilizes the egg. The other options are incorrect because neither the Y chromosome of the father nor the XX chromosome of the mother can alter this 1/2 probability, and the vigour of the parents has no influence on the sex of the offspring.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>55","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"The genotypic ratio of 1 : 2 : 1 in the offspring of a hybrid cross illustrates the law of","images":[],"options":{"A":"use and disuse","B":"dominance","C":"segregation","D":"linkage"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The genotypic ratio of 1:2:1 is a result of Mendel's law of segregation. This law states that during the formation of reproductive cells (gametes), pairs of hereditary traits (genes) for a specific trait separate so that offspring receive one factor from each parent. This results in the genotypic ratio of 1:2:1 in the offspring of a hybrid cross.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>56","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following scientists was involved with organic evolution?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Mendel","B":"Larmarck","C":"Morgan","D":"Pasteur"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Organic evolution refers to the process of the development of living organisms over time. Lamarck was a scientist who is known for his theory of inheritance of acquired characteristics.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>57","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"Which of the following traits may not be important in marriage counselling","images":[],"options":{"A":"Sex-determination","B":"Sickle-cell anaemia","C":"Rhesus factor","D":"Colour of skin"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In marriage counselling, traits that are considered are those that have a significant impact on the health of potential offspring or the compatibility of the couple. These include genetic conditions like sickle-cell anaemia, rhesus factor, and sex-determination. The colour of skin, however, is a physical trait that does not have any impact on health or compatibility, hence it is not important in marriage counselling.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>58","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"In fishes, the brooders return to their parents mouth for","images":[],"options":{"A":"feeding","B":"respiration","C":"breeding","D":"protection"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In certain species of fishes, the brooders return to their parents' mouth for protection. This behavior is known as mouthbrooding, where the parent fish, usually the male, keeps the eggs or young offspring in their mouth for a period of time. This is done to protect the young from predators. The options of feeding, respiration, and breeding are incorrect as the brooders do not return to their parents' mouth for these purposes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>59","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"According to Charles Darwin's Theory of Evolution, natural selection involves the survival of the","images":[],"options":{"A":"weakest","B":"most populous","C":"youngest","D":"Fittest"},"answer":"D","explanation":"According to Charles Darwin's Theory of Evolution, natural selection involves the survival of the fittest. This means that the individuals that are best adapted to their environment are more likely to survive and reproduce. This process leads to the evolution of species over time as beneficial traits become more common in the population. The term 'fittest' in this context doesn't necessarily mean the strongest or the fastest, but rather the one that fits best into its environment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>1999>60","subject":"Biology","year":"1999","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"Which of the following habitats cannot be used for the study of succession?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Savanna grassland","B":"Abandoned farmland","C":"A pond","D":"Well cultivated land"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Succession is the process by which a series of changes occur in an ecological community over time. It often involves the gradual replacement of one plant community by another through a series of stages. For succession to occur, the land must be in a state of disuse or abandonment, allowing for natural processes to take over. A well-cultivated land is constantly being interfered with by human activities such as ploughing, planting, and harvesting, which disrupts the natural succession process. Therefore, a well-cultivated land cannot be used for the study of succession.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"}];